Here's the interface contract I'm designing — use these exact types for your concurrency model:

NotificationChannel { readonly name: string; readonly type: string; send(event: NotificationEvent): Promise<void>; }

NotificationEvent { type: "pipeline.completed"|"pipeline.failed"|"pipeline.aborted"; timestamp: number; pipeline: {name, mode, workspace, elapsedMs}; result: {status, iterations, targetCount, errorCount, errors?, agentStates?} }

NotificationRouter { #channels: NotificationChannel[]; notify(event: NotificationEvent): Promise<void>; // fans out, never throws }

Each channel.send() returns Promise<void>. Router.notify() fans out to all channels and never throws — individual channel failures are logged. Your concurrency model operates on this: bounded concurrency over #channels, fire-and-forget from the pipeline caller's perspective.

