# Concurrency Model: Multi-Channel Notification Dispatch

> **Contract**: Aligned with Lancelot's `NotificationRouter.notify(event)` — fans out to all `NotificationChannel.send()` calls. Router never throws; individual channel failures are logged internally.

## Design Decision: `Promise.allSettled` with Per-Channel Timeout

The pipeline awaits `router.notify(event)` before reporting completion. Notification dispatch is internally parallel with per-channel timeouts so one hung webhook cannot stall the pipeline — but all channels get their chance.

### Why not fire-and-forget?

Fire-and-forget means the pipeline reports completion while notifications are still in flight. If a webhook fails 30 seconds later, the user already saw "completed" and has no indication of the failure. Since the router never throws (allSettled internally), the pipeline can safely await it without try/catch burden.

### Why not `Promise.all`?

`Promise.all` short-circuits on the first rejection. If channel 1 fails, channels 2-N never get their promises settled (their errors become unhandled rejections). `Promise.allSettled` lets every channel attempt delivery and collects per-channel outcomes afterward.

## Model

```
pipeline.run() completes
        │
        ▼
router.notify(event): Promise<void>  ← never throws (allSettled internally)
        │
        ▼
┌───────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  Promise.allSettled([                          │
│    channel1.send(event),  ← 10s timeout        │
│    channel2.send(event),  ← 10s timeout        │
│    channel3.send(event),  ← 5s timeout (file)  │
│  ])                                            │
│    .then(settled => {                          │
│      for (const r of settled) {                │
│        if (r.status === "rejected")            │
│          logger.warn("Notification failed", r) │
│      }                                         │
│    })                                          │
└───────────────────────────────────────────────┘
        │
        ▼
pipeline reports "completed" + summary
```

All channels run in parallel. Each channel's `send()` internally enforces its own timeout and uses the shared `AbortSignal` for cancellation. One hung channel timeouts after its TTL; others proceed unaffected.

## Per-Channel Send (e.g., webhook)

Each `NotificationChannel.send()` implementation is responsible for bounding its own execution:

```typescript
class WebhookChannel implements NotificationChannel {
  readonly name: string;
  readonly type = "webhook";
  #url: string;
  #timeoutMs: number;

  constructor(name: string, url: string, timeoutMs = 10_000) {
    this.name = name;
    this.#url = url;
    this.#timeoutMs = timeoutMs;
  }

  async send(event: NotificationEvent): Promise<void> {
    const controller = new AbortController();
    const timer = setTimeout(() => controller.abort(), this.#timeoutMs);

    try {
      const response = await fetch(this.#url, {
        method: "POST",
        headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },
        body: JSON.stringify(event),
        signal: controller.signal,
      });
      if (!response.ok) {
        throw new Error(`HTTP ${response.status}: ${await response.text().catch(() => "")}`);
      }
    } finally {
      clearTimeout(timer);
    }
  }
}
```

### Timeout per channel type

| Channel | Default Timeout | Rationale |
|---------|----------------|-----------|
| Webhook | 10s | HTTP round-trip + small processing buffer |
| File append | 5s | Local I/O, fast but disk could be contended |
| stdout (future) | 3s | Trivial, mostly diagnostic |
| Slack/Discord (future) | 10s | Same as webhook |

### Bounded concurrency?

**Not needed at this scale.** Configs will have 1-5 notification channels. Five parallel fetches are trivial for the event loop. If a future scale target (e.g., 50+ webhooks) emerges, add a semaphore-based pool:

```typescript
// Future: bounded pool for many channels
class NotificationRouter {
  #channels: NotificationChannel[];
  #pool: ConcurrencyPool;

  constructor(channels: NotificationChannel[], maxConcurrent = 5) {
    this.#channels = channels;
    this.#pool = new ConcurrencyPool(maxConcurrent);
  }

  async notify(event: NotificationEvent): Promise<void> {
    const results = await Promise.allSettled(
      this.#channels.map(ch => this.#pool.run(() => ch.send(event)))
    );
    for (const r of results) {
      if (r.status === "rejected") logger.warn("Notification failed", { reason: r.reason });
    }
  }
}
```

Omit for v1 — YAGNI.

## Cancellation

If the pipeline is aborted (user cancels, process terminates), the existing `AbortSignal` can propagate through to each channel's fetch via the `NotificationEvent` or a shared signal on the router. Aborted sends reject with an `AbortError`; `Promise.allSettled` treats rejection the same as any other failure — logged, not thrown.

Important: **the pipeline aborts in-progress sends but does not skip notification dispatch**. Cancelling mid-notification is fine — `Promise.allSettled` resolves as soon as all channels settle (either completed or aborted).

## Error Isolation

- Channel 1 hangs (timeout after 10s) → rejection captured by `allSettled`, logged as `"timeout"`
- Channel 2 succeeds in 200ms → fulfills normally
- Channel 3 DNS failure → rejection captured, logged as `"fetch failed"`

All three settle independently. `Promise.allSettled` collects all outcomes. The router logs warnings for failed channels and returns cleanly (`Promise<void>` resolved).

## Integration Point

In `handleRun()` (extension.ts), after `buildSummaryMessage()`:

```typescript
// Existing: send summary to conversation
pi.sendMessage(summaryMessage, { triggerTurn: false });

// New: dispatch notifications via configured router
if (def.notifications) {
  const router = new NotificationRouter(def.notifications);
  await router.notify({
    type: `pipeline.${result.status}`,
    timestamp: Date.now(),
    pipeline: { name: def.name, mode: def.mode, workspace, elapsedMs },
    result: { status: result.status, iterations: result.iterations,
              targetCount: def.targetCount, errorCount: result.errors.length },
  });
  // Router never throws — failed channels were logged internally
}
```

The `await` here means the TUI's "completed" notification and widget clear happen AFTER notification dispatch completes (or times out). Total worst-case latency: `max(perChannelTimeout)` = 10s. Acceptable — the user gets accurate completion status without a hidden failure surface.

## Summary

| Concern | Decision |
|---------|----------|
| Execution | `Promise.allSettled` — parallel, isolated, never throws from router |
| Timeout | Per-channel, configurable, 10s default for webhooks |
| Hung channel | Contained — other channels unaffected; hung channel rejects after TTL |
| Error isolation | One failure → logged, others proceed; caller sees clean resolution |
| Cancellation | Per-channel `AbortController` + optional shared signal; settles promptly |
| Bounded concurrency | Defer to v2 — 1-5 channels don't need it |
| Retry | Not in dispatch layer — channel implementations own retry policy |
| Ordering | Parallel — no ordering guarantees needed |

